The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", has issued a brochure
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several things in common.
They are more likely to be older, unable to work, for example due to health reasons, single and childless.
The one who "becomes" a witch is sent to isolation so she doesn't endanger the rest of the village.
"A man's fate is very rare".
"Even young healthy women are not excluded because they help with work and childbirth", explains a religious sister who cares for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their community in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government has now decided to take action against the unusual "social measure".
She's issued a brochure that should help reduce the witch hunt.
It's got a catch.
