The office includes a kindergarten, the architects understood.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to also conceal a mini-school with all its associated amenities - colorful walls, fancy furniture, a pile of toys, and even a miniature outdoor playground.
Since October last year, it has been open to the children of Arch.Design employees.
The architectural design company Arch.Design, whose studios have produced a number of important buildings in Brno, had been counting on space for its mini-school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs nearly 90 people, mostly baby boomers, and it cares about women designers and architects getting back to work quickly.
Along with the possibility of reduced hours, the nursery is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees under a social programme.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine demanding work with child care.
The mini-school was designed by Arch.Design's own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-school is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the Czech State budget.
Thanks to grant funding (grant of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and for two years to provide qualified staff and operations.
After the financial grant (2 years) is exhausted, Arch.Design is obliged to operate the mini-school at its own expense for 3 years.
The project took one year to prepare and the company Economy Rating was instrumental in the grant application.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, and are cared for by a nurse and a teacher at the school all day long. Children can attend kindergarten without age restrictions, although most are over 3 years old.
Since it is a "mini-school", only five children may attend at a time, but more may be switched during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the nursery regardless of the hierarchy of positions in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the programme content of the mini-school is comparable to the framework programme for pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they also receive quality education - from basic knowledge to preparation for school, including English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer for children to use.
The presence of young children in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time and avoid stressful situations with late pick-ups from kindergartens far from the parents' workplace.
This makes the parents more productive.
It is not surprising that a loyal employee-employer relationship is naturally created here.
Arch.Design thus became one of the Czech companies that offer significant benefits when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through this program strengthened personnel marketing.
The bone house is still fascinating after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of an ancient lizard, the stairs look like the back of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The house was nicknamed the House of Bones by the locals because of its organic shapes.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The facade of the house is a play of dream lines, gentle colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
When you look closely, you can see geometry, rhythm, and a well-thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, being illuminated to enhance the impression of bright colors.
The curvature and twisting of shapes to the same extent occurs in interiors.
Wood in waves mimics window frames, railings, door decorations, and peepholes and planks.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample district on the busy Passeig de Gracia 43, was created by the reconstruction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The Casa Batlló, the officer's house, but Antoni Gaudí did not design it himself.
He was assisted by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaics on the facade were created.
Many other designers and artists worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs for Casa Batlló launched Jujola's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudi's Casa Mila and the Güell Park, which houses other works by Gaudi.
The house was soon nicknamed "The House of Bones" by the locals because of its organic shapes.
Others have called it a "swinging house" because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows.
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted on the top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house, with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Strange may seem their forty-five degree inclination.
Gaudí did not respect the building codes of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the start of construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data given by the city about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city council was shocked and asked for a repair.
For example, the council was upset that the building was interfering with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
The repair never took place, on the contrary: just 15 days after the city's call, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) a permit to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
The gallery on the second floor had a social lounge and the bedroom and private part of the apartment on the third floor.
The ground floor was rented out to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building is lined with stairs that lead up to the roof terrace itself.
The main elements of the reconstruction were the removal of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on the modern concept of space interconnection.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the living room door and the larger company can communicate comfortably without losing the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction received, in addition to the new facade, an unconventional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play with light, the blue and white glazed tiles that line the courtyard, and the lanterns are also impressive.
The two-color game provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was easy to bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, which was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, is open to the public.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and luxurious apartment open to the public.
The owners decided to do so only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous designer.
They persisted in the inspection, finding it to be a very profitable business and, moreover, extended the inspection to include common and attic areas, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee is certainly not negligible, at €16.50, and students, pensioners, groups and tourist cardholders enjoy a 20% discount.
The sum far exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the real atmosphere of a house with dragon towers, you must quickly befriend one of the inhabitants of the apartment building and visit him directly at home.
How to choose mattresses and grills: women have different requirements than men
Not the sumptuous frame of the bed, but the quality of the surface, the mattress and the grille, are the basis of a really good bed.
However, they must be harmonised to suit the particular user.
Many factors determine the choice, from weight, height, age, health, to the owner's sex.
The type of interior in which the mattress and grille are installed is also important.
Typical example?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages where bats routinely bathe, as they "heat up" more slowly.
In addition, they have a significantly higher weight than standard polyurethane mattresses.
They need to be turned over regularly.
If they do not have many vents in the core and are still on solid plates, they retain moisture: mold may also appear underneath.
Choice is also determined by habit.
Those who have spent time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softener are often used, will find it difficult to feel comfortable on low, hard surfaces.
"I guess all the hockey players coming back from the NHL complained that they couldn't sleep here".
"For their bruised shoulders, paws and hips, they needed a mattress with a softening layer of lazy foam".
"These are even recommended for people with diabetes who have a nervous system disorder that makes them misrepresent the 'information' from the joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamczik, a specialist in upholstered furniture.
That's why many hockey players and other customers needed flax foam mattresses years ago.
"Today it's all right, the right mattress has Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico".
You don't have to be an NHL fighter to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
It optimizes its hardness and shape according to the heat it absorbs, or adapts to your warm body.
You're not pushed, you don't roll over at night like you've been through a tough fight.
You'll just sleep better.
Flaxseed foam also acts as a protection against bedbugs.
When choosing a mattress size, add the length of the foot to your height, which is usually about seven to eight inches [21 to 34 cm].
A man and a woman who are about six feet tall need a bed that's six to seven feet tall.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double, so 180 cm.
For single beds, for example singles, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For your convenience and possible visitation.
"Otherwise, the bed width rule is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly curved at the elbow", advises Helena Prokopová, a master of the Stools and Decorators Guild, who has been working on the issue of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for many years and who lectures on it at trade schools.
In a double bed, each person needs a separate grille and mattress, but be careful when buying to adjust the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, you have no choice but to mount grills at different heights, but you may not be able to do so for every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, spring-shaped types at least 15 cm, of which at least 3 cm should be counted on the moulding and curing layer.
"You should definitely not feel the springs when you touch them or sit on the mattress", warns Helena Prokopová.
Every mattress requires a certain type of grill.
Full-fledged beds with mattresses and underpants like conjoined twins have no place in bedrooms.
Mattresses are poorly ventilated, and you can't wash the soot, which is common nowadays.
And since we normally sweat 0.2 to 0.75 liters a night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress will start to look like one big (and stuffy) grid.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about mattresses lasting up to 25 years, or even a lifetime warranty.
But everything has its "buts".
So, practical advice from the sellers: For mattresses that are 120 or 140 centimeters wide, keep the removable cover on and add a mattress cover that can be easily removed and washed.
Although the mattress liners that are commonly made today are woven all over the perimeter, so when you untie it, you get two parts (very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), the manipulation in larger types (and in one person) could resemble a fight between a lightweight in the ring and a heavyweight.
Do you have a hard disk instead of a grill in your bed?
I never will!
No more than a bed for one night's visit.
However, provide ventilation holes (if not already) for the board and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (including Taschenfederkern) and a coating of pepper.
Polyurethane mattresses are not suitable for this type of foundation.
For non-locking lamellar grids with 14 to 18 lamels, latex or sandwich mattresses (e.g. combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable, but you will always benefit from grids with a higher number of lamels, 28 or more, where the lamels in the thigh area are doubled and their rigidity can be adjusted.
The positioning lamellar grilles do not include spring-shaped mattresses, as they do not respond to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the lamellae, a shoulder cradle is also available.
This is a special grip that allows the sleeper to press or even tilt the sleeper's shoulder.
For men with "shoulders all over their backs", it's definitely an important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers are now remembering it, and in the "Gentlemen's" they have begun to use a softening zone in the shoulder area.
They also remember women - they give them a softer surface at the hip.
For the most demanding customers, wings or slabs with so-called multitooling are designed.
The pressure is distributed in multiple points and the voltage is reduced.
Of course, once you use the wrong pillow (big and "smooth") on the right mattress and grille, most of the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the tips should only touch the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
The appropriate size is recommended to be 50 x 60 cm, which is preferred in Scandinavia, for example.
When lying on the side, the pillow should balance (together with the shoulder cradle of the grille or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original straw-filled grass beds.
The reason is that manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials, or at least ingredients.
It's just that the trend is mattress bio.
The petroleum raw materials used to make polyurethane foams are replaced by natural oils such as hops and soybeans.
So, soy is used by almost every major manufacturer.
"The bio of mattresses means that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin", explains Petr Vašiček of Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used in the manufacture of mattress linings, one of the first being aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules to release the fresh scent of the forest or lavender.
There are also separate men's and women's sections.
While a man is "cool" by a plant extract from the birch to allow the mattress's sweat to absorb heat and cool the body, women are "melted" by the sheets.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making it warmer for the weaker sex.
The favorite of the day?
The mattress made of cold foam (with larger pores and a broken cellular structure) is more breathable than conventional polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
Combining different hardnesses of cold foam and "lazy" foam, multi-zone mattresses are created that know exactly where to place the head, thighs, and heels.
You'll pay from seven thousand crowns and up for a good mattress.
Those that meet the health criteria, have a lower VAT rate, are considered medical devices.
Gumotex was the first company in the Czech Republic to achieve this advantage.
It's not easy to save on mattresses and grills.
Sometimes, for example, promotions by manufacturers or retailers may be used, offering two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, Magniflex offers Duofreeze mattresses with all Memory foam in the lid for $11,990.
The other one, of course, is free.
The era of lazy, or viscoelastic, foams with open cell structures and high density was ushered in at a "cosmic" pace by the material Tempur.
It was originally created as a NASA material because astronauts were exposed to enormous overload during launch.
Temperature softened in warmth, solidified in cold.
It adapts perfectly to the warmth of the human body and distributes the pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal for preventing bedwetting, but also for increasing sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only in mattresses but also in medical products, such as special foot pads that relieve the leg and the vascular system.
Domestic producers use Eucatherm C foam, Twinsaver and the like.
People-tracking devices want more and more parents, so they want to watch their children
Fear of their own child is leading more and more people to the idea of GPS surveillance.
The system, originally designed to track cars, can also track people's movements, helping in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anika Janatkov.
The device is about the size of a matchbox, but soon it may be as big as a watch.
Many people were terrified by the disappearance of Annika and began to search for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of their privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that it is not spying, but another means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I admit that in certain cases, there may be misuse of such devices, such as when they are put in the bag of someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case".
"Mostly, customers actually buy it for safety reasons", Pilin added.
He said that a child should always know what the "box" is for and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bochko warns that if a child does not want to wear something like this, he will simply get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how they willfully lose things when they don't want to be in control".
"Parents used to have high expectations for cell phones, but they can be turned off just like these surveillance devices", says Bočková.
It is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"In the case of an attempted kidnapping, the perpetrator will virtually always make sure that the child has no electronic devices that could reveal his location".
"Now it's the phone".
"As surveillance devices become more widespread, they will be sought after, because their sales will surely be fueled by massive advertising".
"In that case, the criminals will always be one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, he admits that such a device can help in the event of a sudden attack by a paedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the tracking device is destroyed immediately after an attack, its presence can help.
'The device can be set to transmit the position periodically after a certain time.'
'If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available.'
"More expensive devices have in-built tilt meters, so even if a person slips and remains motionless, the device will send out an immediate warning with a position indicator", says Čech.
He said that a similar service could be provided by smart mobile phones with navigation, which could be accessed by downloading special software.
The problem with the current surveillance units is that they're either devices the size of matchboxes or smaller mobile phones.
They're always in danger of being lost.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, therefore, a device that looks like a regular digital watch is now being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in that the potential aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all".
"Or he will only know them after a while and that may give the police extra time", he adds.
Whether the tracking devices evolve into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology as is used for vehicle surveillance.
It is a combination of GPS positioning (used by standard car navigation systems) and a mobile phone function that reports the current position of the vehicle.
