Longer index finger than ring finger means lower risk of cancer
Men who have a forefinger longer than the ring have a lower risk of prostate cancer.
That's the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It could be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results suggest that the relative length of a finger can serve as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60", said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially when combined with genetic risk or other risk factors, such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
More than half of the study participants had a pointer on their right hand shorter than their ring finger.
They were as likely to get prostate cancer as 19 percent of those with the same length of fingers.
However, for those with a forefinger longer than the ring, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men by age 60, it was down by 87 percent.
The length of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones that the baby is exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer reading.
Previous research has shown that testosterone is the one that promotes prostate cancer growth.
Leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told the Czech News Agency that he was familiar with the study, but that he did not think the relationship between finger length and cancer was "fully proven".
