Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Crime is a bigger concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered by many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of a recent Latinobarometer survey of 18 countries, published exclusively in The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the region.
In this year's survey, which was conducted in September and early October, two related things dominate.
The first is that Latin America is a pretty cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries on the Pacific Rim in South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy was recovering from a sharp drop in output last year.
But only about half of those polled in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous regions, are Democratic-minded, which is lower than the regional average (see Graph 2).
Some 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but a large increase compared with 25% in 2001 (Chart 3).
Some 34% said they trusted the parliament in their country and 45% trusted the government, again the same figures as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, democracy in Latin America was undermined by the economic crisis.
The support was given during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries had suffered only a brief recession and were enjoying a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year to 32 percent.)
However, the mood varies across a wide range of countries (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in the widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has worsened.
For only the second time since surveys were started, more respondents across Latin America see crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
About 31 percent say that they or a close relative was a victim of crime last year, down from 38 percent last year and the lowest since 1995.
The more massive economic performance is reflected in the growing support for private enterprise and the market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region say private enterprise is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will enable their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same opinion (and 80% support private enterprise there), even though their leftist president Hugo Chávez is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the field, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9% unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, up from 11% last year).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
