Arsenic-resistant microbes increase the possibility of new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients opens up the space for the search for new life forms on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, and they say it's a sign that life has possibilities that are beyond the main elements that have been considered basic.
"This organism has a dual ability".
"It can grow either from phosphorus or arsenic".
"This is very strange, but it is not proof of any form of truly 'extraterrestrial' life", commented Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report, which appeared in the online edition of the journal Science on Thursday.
For a long time, six basic elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur - were considered essential for life.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after phosphorus is replaced by arsenic.
"You'll be amazed at what's still possible", said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
This finding is significant for the search for life beyond Earth, because researchers need to be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report of this discovery released to discuss it, which did not reveal the details of the find, has caused widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to utilize other elements that drive biochemistry and that a set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life", explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure", added Cockell.
It wasn't a fluke.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar, so she thought that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to replace one with the other.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus".
"The result is that organisms have a very difficult time separating these elements".
"But arsenic is so different that it doesn't work like phosphorus, and once it gets into the body, it starts to work in biochemical processes", Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better under the influence of phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, there is a greater chance that a form of life that uses arsenic could occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus is not new, but no such example has ever been found.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it could have been used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways of creating life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth", said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
