The lion's ready to roar again now that MGM's restructuring has been given final approval by the court.
After 18 months of upheaval and uncertainty, MGM has finally been given the green light to start over.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York City on Thursday officially blessed a "pre-packaged" plan by creditors to settle about $5 billion in debt, clearing the way for an 86-year-old entertainment company that focuses on producing and producing movies and television shows.
With Thursday's finding that the plan meets the requirements of U.S. bankruptcy rules, MGM remains free of legal barriers to re-launching Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the principal executives of the downsized studio.
