The D.A.s are not gonna charge Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have cleared Senator John Ensign of criminal charges related to his affair with a former campaign adviser and his efforts to secure lobbying, the senator's lawyers announced Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, a Nevada Republican who was, until the scandal, considered a possible Republican candidate for president in 2012.
Mr. Ensign's office said it was "very pleased" with the decision that followed the nearly year-long investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action before the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers said that the Justice Department "has informed us that Senator Ensign will no longer be the subject of an investigation and that it has no plans to bring any further charges against him in this matter".
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The decision came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who argued that there was strong evidence that Mr. Ensign was preparing to violate the federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents that were published in October 2009 in the New York Times stated that Mr. Ensign was helping Douglas Hampton, one of his assistants, secure a lucrative lobbying effort that was to lead to the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton used to work as the treasurer for the Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political supporters to find work for Mr. Hampton and supported their views after Mr. Hampton was hired to lobby for them, so much so that they cite documents and interviews.
Since Hampton was, until recently, Mr. Ensign's assistant, he was legally barred from lobbying his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts say the unusual handling of Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were friends before the affair, appeared to violate the lobbying ban.
The evidence that has been released "shows that this is a clear case of preparation for a violation of the law", said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients under investigation by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasons for the decision in Senator Ensign's case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department is cautious about political prosecutions after a string of setbacks, including last year's decision to suspend the prosecution of former Senator Ted Stevens amid accusations of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors "clearly hid their guns", said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, the advocacy group that filed several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"It basically shows that the laws don't apply to high-ranking government officials", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he was called by the Attorney General's Office on Monday and then the next day, telling him that the Department had found no charges against his client.
