Can politeness overcome the abyss?
After a campaign that was notable for its offensiveness and negativity, there was little courtesy this week in Washington.
Is this the first patchwork of real cooperation between two political parties or just an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan fighting in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and House leaders yielded no major findings on the key issues that must be discussed during the session.
But in any case, it was a polite discussion of the two parties' differences of opinion, as well as defining their shared responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of party politics.
Wednesday's public meeting of the President's deficit committee was also civil, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close cooperation over several months has built up a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gulf that still divides the members.
And it's hard to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both parties are now in a testing period, probing each other for signs of collegiality and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed party war.
Therefore, the Tuesday meeting and its subsequent evaluation by the participants was also carried out with minimal demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too broad and too deep to suggest a quick change in the conditions that have prevailed here for the past two years.
Whether it's a matter of taxes, spending, health care or rights, the two sides are miles apart.
However, the November election was prepared by Washington at least quickly.
"It's not a question of whether regulatory matters have changed", said Pete Wehner, the Bush administrator, now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"They are inevitable after the election.
The election stirred up the party's emotions and then they shut up.
It's good".
On a number of issues, especially those to be discussed in the House, Republicans and Democrats have little chance of finding a solution.
Bush's tax cuts are over at the end of the year, and nobody's looking at it favorably.
Both parties want to find a way to protect some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Like the likely compromise on unemployment benefits just because Republicans can't watch them support tax cuts for the wealthy while denying unemployed people unemployment benefits.
After Tuesday's White House meeting, there is already a growing optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of a new landmark treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on critical issues will not necessarily lead to a two-party relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, it's a probable period of disagreement, or even inevitable, he said.
"After the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term returns to one of the confrontations", he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism - which is widespread to a large extent - that politeness would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I look at everything that happens between now and 2012 as a shadow box, with the main events happening in 2012", he said.
The reasons are largely related to the assembling of the new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters who helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of exaggeration, knowing they must live up to their promises and cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
These supportive lines are clear in initial responses to the deficit recommendations, which include reform of the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Joint Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult tasks in Washington, and they are, in their view, to bring the deficit issue to the public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to present their plan as an official recommendation and thus fight to get as close to that number as possible.
The greatest resistance is among elected officials on the jury, who suggest that in the case of financial matters, we have, at least today, little basis or will for compromise.
Galston predicts two stages in the battle between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of partisan conflicts, with Republicans challenging Obama to address the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of more partisan cooperation.
What will cause the shift?
The public opinion.
There's plenty of evidence that despite the partisanship in the last election, most Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If it could be headed for a dead end, as it was in 1995, then both sides will be watching the public reaction very carefully.
Anyone who threatens to lose votes will likely change course and seek compromise.
That may be an optimistic view of things.
The bias and bias is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and it shows that there's a bigger ideological divide between Obama and the congressional Republicans than there was between the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to the more important elections in 2012.
Based on that reality, the courtesy that has emerged this week would be welcome by many Americans.
But it will take a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on issues that still divide them.
