Known as the "butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge regime, the commander remains popular in this remote Khmer Rouge state in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered, a long-standing loyalty is also being broken in Anlong Veng.
In April, victims were allowed to confront people who were part of the regime in public at the Truth and Reconciliation Forum.
In June, the government provided textbooks that explain the history of the Khmer Rouge and their former soldiers to children for the first time.
And in July, the UN and a Cambodian court jointly lifted the first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former leader of the notorious Tuol Sleng violent group, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as the Spirit, to 35 years in prison.
With each such advance, unrest among the Khmer Rouge veterans in Anlong Veng grew, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is anger and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they are powerless to do anything", said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that studies the regime.
"For them, life among the Khmer Rouge was beautiful, but the regime became a symbol of evil".
"It divides families".
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew Pol Pot's government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its troops fled to the Cambodian-Thai border.
There they started an uprising that lasted until the last movement in December 1998.
Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary ran guerrilla wars from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, while Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement, the country was led to the first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to move to a government that culminated in the surrender of Ieng Sara in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998 and Ta Mok, who survived, was captured by government forces in the nearby Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Their patrons no longer cared for them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters have been reduced to ordinary Cambodian rural life, and many of them have nostalgic memories of the time of the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge have retained their local government positions in exchange for their weapons, their position remains weak as unskilled farmers.
"These people have had minimal benefit from the surrender", said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which runs public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are surrounded by the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime".
"They were raised without any idea of conducting business".
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling down as a poor farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good", he said.
"The Mock fed them all".
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of everything ourselves".
The ongoing Khmer Rouge trial has also raised concerns.
Early next year, the court will begin investigating Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court has a mandate to prosecute the executives and people responsible for the crimes, but it has not been said whether it will proceed with the four cases.
It was not enough to calm the anxiety in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a regional leader in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Documentation Centre in Cambodia that she oversaw the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that likely killed thousands of forced laborers.
On a steamy evening recently, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her wooden house on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun began to set and shadows appeared over the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about her past among the Khmer Rouge.
If she was subpoenaed, she wouldn't go.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable", she said.
"If there are any more criminal prosecutions, there will be war".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would ensue if the court sought additional suspects, although experts and historians disagree.
"Cambodia must dig a deep hole and bury the past", he said.
But confronting the past is just what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation in Khmer relations means blinding the broken pieces", he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand each other".
The Centre has published the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, 75 pages long and titled 'The History of Democratic Cambodia'.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as an appendix to the Ministry of Education's history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
Like many people in Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng knew little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's connection to the regime.
Vale Touchak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand important parts of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he took home the book for study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the courts", he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people the court will prosecute".
Such resistance makes the process of reconciliation more difficult and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, textbooks and the courts are starting to make an impact, he added.
The Khmer Rouge still have a strong spell here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, a path lined with weeds and littered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black soot covered with a resin-plated roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
