"I was really fascinated by the fact that they want a place for the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit".
"This proves that the process is working", said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear security.
Clinton called the deal "a very significant, important step" by Belarus.
Obama promised in Prague in April 2009 to secure all sensitive nuclear materials worldwide within four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium stockpiles.
Belarus will be seventh.
A dozen countries did it under George W. Bush.
At the time of the Obama nuclear security summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko announced that his nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially the basis for the weapon and less enriched uranium", Lukashenko said.
"It's our commodity... We're not going to make dirty bombs and we're not going to sell it to anyone".
"We're only using it for research purposes, that's all".
However, Belarus joined the United States a few months ago and expressed interest in reaching an agreement.
The first commitment to remove Belarusian uranium in October was particularly complicated because the material was slightly irradiated, officials said.
It was loaded onto a special train that traveled more than 1,300 miles to a Russian storage and disposal facility, officials said.
The second operation was closed on Monday and was conducted by air, officials said.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on the program, most of it to supply a Belarusian research institute with low-enriched uranium, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
"Everything was very carefully coordinated and managed on the basis of trust", leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, the Department of Energy's official for Global Threat Reduction.
The James Martin Center for the Study of Nuclear Nonproliferation estimated this year that Belarus has at least 88 pounds of uranium usable for weapons production.
According to the Joint Declaration, Belarus will endeavour to remove its stockpiles by 2012.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, primarily because of Lukashenko's brutal crackdown on human rights.
But Wednesday's statement suggests the possibility of a gradual meltdown.
"Welcoming progress on these global security issues, the United States and Belarus recognized that a more consistent respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains the foundation for improving relations between the two countries and is essential for the progress of the country and its people", he said.
