A Catalan cell has provided thousands of passports to al-Qaeda.
In addition to the seven arrested in Barcelona, three others were detained in Thailand.
The seven Pakistanis and one Nigerian detained by the General Information Office in Barcelona were part of a Thai-led jihadist cell that provided passports to various Al-Qaeda groups, including the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam and Lashkar-e-Taiba, the latter of which was responsible for the 2008 Mumbai attacks that killed 106 people.
The Ministry of Interior attaches great importance to the investigation of this matter, aiming to ensure that the "Operation Kampai" weakens the Al-Qaeda counterfeiting apparatus at the international level and "thus limits its operational capabilities".
Investigators estimate that during the two years the cell was active in Catalonia, it could have sent thousands of passports to Thailand, where they were then forged and then supplied to groups that make up the criminal galaxy of the Al-Qaeda organization so that their "warriors" could travel with impunity across borders in Europe and other Western countries.
This broken cell was not the only active jihad network in Europe, and therefore, in addition to the Thai services, other European police units were involved in these investigations, and it cannot be ruled out that similar interventions like the one in Barcelona last Tuesday night will not take place in other European countries in the coming days.
In connection with this operation (which captured the Pakistanis Junaid Humayun, Atiqur Rehman, Jabran Asghar, Malik Iftikhar Ahmad, Mohammad Saddique Khan Begum, Tanveer Arshad and the Nigerian Babatunde Agunbiade), another operation was developed in Thailand, which captured the Pakistanis Muhammad Athar Butt and Zeeshan Ehsan Butt and the Thai Sirikan Kilayajbumrung.
It was these same men who ran a cell in Spain and other European countries from Bangkok.
The Catalan network, part of which was liquidated in 2009, mainly stole passports from tourists that met the demands of the Islamists.
That means the documents had to belong to men between the ages of 25 and 45, they had to be valid for several years and they had to be unmarked visas.
The investigation documents emphasize that no facts are known to link the Catalan detainees to the Mumbai bombing, although the perpetrator of these attacks, Lashkar-e-Taiba, was said to be one of the groups that accepted passports stolen in Spain and then forged in Thailand.
It is worth noting, however, that a few days before this attack, about a thousand dollars were sent from Catalonia by a wire agency, which were "put" into the purchase of mobile phone cards, which were later used by members of the "commando" that killed 106 people.
