Red Bull triumphs in Formula One with a secret weapon from Siemens
The software suggests improvements in vehicles in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the Formula One series in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been one of surprise and success.
At first, no one took the prospects of this new team very seriously, and despite the recent upward trend, everyone was betting on Fernando Alonso's Ferrari triumph.
Without wanting to diminish the riding abilities of the champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, or the possibilities of the Renault engine that powers his car, a legend was born in the world of Formula One - the "secret weapon" that multinational Siemens put into the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful ride-simulation software that a German company launched in 2007 for the purpose of long-distance motorsport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software tool, has been used to design assembly lines in manufacturing plants around the world, in power plants, and for high-precision machines.
The aim is to reproduce the product or to simulate the process faithfully before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary errors and expense.
PLM has facilitated the development of the Canon camera, the Sukhoi aircraft and the most famous Nissan commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that using this software device, the Red Bull team was able to make "in a matter of hours, in near real time", modifications and improvements that would otherwise be detected during races and tests.
Russwurm says that in 1992 the stables employed an average of 10 technicians, who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements in one season.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 highly skilled young professionals equipped with powerful IT technology, who analyse and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is capable of analysing and improving all elements of Red Bull racing cars with the exception of the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
Modifications to materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features.
Changes can be converted from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced laser manufacturing systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation on this technical capability is the amount of $40 million, which is the maximum that each Formula One team can spend in each season to improve its competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a high-tech factory about 30 miles outside London to design and build its racing cars.
These are two buildings that are off limits to visitors - especially journalists.
Everything that happens here is considered "a great secret".
The list of participants in this project is 580 people, including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Red Bull in Formula One is undoubtedly the new champion Sebastian Vettel.
But behind the immense technological resources the energy drink brand has invested in its participation in the racetrack, there are other protagonists whose help is invaluable, yet unknown.
Steve Nevey, chief technology officer, says that five years ago, you could say that advances in vehicle research and development contributed to 50 percent of the victory, and the rest was due to the riders.
Today, that ratio has changed and technology accounts for 85% of the successes, while pilots contribute 15%.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computer technology, as they are "unpredictable gladiators".
