Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but it set the conditions for the Union as a whole.
Tensions in the markets provoked a two-pronged government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed new adaptation measures, ranging from a reduction in taxes for SMEs, through the regulation of private intermediary agencies and the abolition of the 426 euros for unemployed without benefits, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA (Spanish Airports and Air Traffic Management), the managers of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the state lottery.
Vice-President Elena Salgadova, supported by former Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in triggering the current crisis.
How do we interpret these movements?
It should be noted that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is the next step in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which contradicts the idea of keeping old traditions that is held by a large part of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro area, which would include Germany, but also Austria and the Netherlands, for example, while the southern countries would leave the currency area.
The second is a return to the march - although it may seem like sci-fi now, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to rework the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, fiscal austerity, fines for the guilty states, possible deferrals for some of them, and an extension of the possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for slander now.
First, after the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission encouraged deficits in 2009, the German government pulled out of the sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of the contradiction between what Germany considered to be the right course (fiscal austerity and fiscal stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The other was shown by these Central European countries, as Merkel painfully delayed the decision to rescue Greece.
It was already the subject of sharp criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel has again come out with a clear position when she demanded that the European Union conventions be reformed to allow the rescue of a Member State and at the same time to make it mandatory for private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it hastened the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat moderate form, has been approved and we should be following the Union's reform process over the coming months, which should enable these measures to be taken from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it will not cross.
And he tells us all that although measures are now needed, which he apparently disagrees with, the old euro will be finished by this date.
The year 2013 will mark the birth of a new currency area, in which countries that break the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to declare a deferral of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we must take a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
The alternative, based on debt and building, with the huge gaps in the balance of payments that prevailed during the boom years of Spain, is simply not going to be tolerated.
The offer is clear.
And we would be wrong not to understand that.
It is not just a matter of restoring the government deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much tougher.
And the worst part is, under these conditions, we could be wrong.
I hope these current turbulences will be replaced by a more calm atmosphere.
And that we will take the opportunity they give us until the spring of 2013.
Prime Minister Zapatero also seems to have understood this, and his double declaration (reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big business and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that despite criticism of Merkel, the idea that things need to be fixed has been opened up.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is here, and it doesn't seem to want to move it.
And of the options that can be considered, leaving the eurozone full of less serious countries cannot be ruled out.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that they warned us.
Sport and circumvention
The finches Alonso and Ramos showed against Ajax show ingenuity, not the intention to escape punishment.
The allegedly fabricated expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramose) from the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November has caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike behaviour and whether, eventually, UEFA should not punish both players.
It is well known that a few minutes before the end of the game (which their team had clearly won), the players named one by one deliberately lost time at the time of the foul to provoke the referee, who showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will complete the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in the top of their group - and will be able to proceed to the next stage, stripped of their cards.
In the end, the UEFA disciplinary committee gave coach José Mourinho a two-match ban and the guilty players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos of football, the rules that are not written, but they're followed.
Part of the debate in this case has been the participation of Real Madrid (which boasts of its generosity and honour in its anthem and has already fined its players for similar acts), and apparently also the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
In any event, the debate is whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts are circumventing the law; they are indeed acts which respect the rules of sport, the meaning of which, of course, it seems to be trying to circumvent.
The damage to the sporting spirit is being dealt with.
One of the requirements of sporting conduct is the physical inviolability of the opponents, which was not violated in these cases, i.e. no violent play took place.
Another of the characteristics of a clean game is to avoid that players have an advantage over the opposing team by their offence - which has not happened here either.
So the paradox of the Real Madrid players' actions is that there was no what we normally characterize as a ruse or circumvention of the law, no hidden violation of the rules to avoid punishment, but rather this behavior was to be as visible as possible in order to receive punishment.
They waited and liked to be punished.
Another question, though, is what benefit will be gained by the guilty ones from their willful transgression.
It is important to note that the opponent is not at a disadvantage and that there is no advantage in the current match, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club won't be able to count on these players.
The obvious advantage is that players start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage in the long run and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team may be eliminated, and besides this action, the players will reimburse the penalty and go to the second round of cards, where one card less than in the first round is enough to eliminate.
So as the rounds continue, it's not entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations are not against the spirit of sport, which is to make strategic decisions that allow for maximum benefit within the rules.
In the case we are discussing, the players did not aim to avoid a penalty (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding punishment or running from it.
While the line between common sense and circumvention is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly common sense.
