The bidding war for Christmas parties in Barcelona
The calendar dictates that this year's avalanche of reservations will be on December 16th and 17th.
There are increasingly more celebrations paid for by the employees themselves, who want to spend between 20 and 30 euros.
Like Turkish honey or the lottery, the arrival of December brings back the pre-Christmas parties, which still act as an oxygen bomb for restaurants and leisure facilities in Barcelona, but which have been reduced by the crisis to a fight to win customers by lowering prices: almost everyone wants to spend 20 to 30 euros on food, according to the businessmen and associations in the sector surveyed.
To complete the complication of the numbers, the calendar this year (when Christmas Day fell on a Friday) concentrated requests for the week from December 13, creating an avalanche of reservations for the peak days (16 and 17), while the previous week there was almost no traffic.
As has been the case since 2008, when the lean years began, many companies have cancelled group parties for budgetary reasons.
To keep up with the tradition, many employees pay for parties out of their own pockets.
Regardless of the situation, many are demanding prices that are too high, says Gaieta Farras, president of the Gremi de Restauració de Barcelona.
The restaurant's representative is hesitant to predict the festivities this month.
"People think twice before making reservations".
"They want to go out, but they're cautious about the price", he adds.
Shops will do well "by offering quality and good service at a favourable price", he says, recalling that the crisis has led to a downward trend in customers, with most customers now willing to spend around €25.
A survey of the various facilities shows that the largest surge in reservations is on the evening of December 17th.
The Soteras Group reports a real boom in bookings for this Friday, with the most requests being for spending up to 30 euros, which they have adapted to the menus offered, whose total prices are between 25 and 30 euros.
In another important company, Andilana, which has 16 establishments in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), the peculiarity of this year's calendar has brought more early bookings since the beginning of November.
"We have done everything possible and impossible to keep up with last year's prices, and our menus, which are for everyone to choose from, range from 19.95 to 30 euros", they report.
The AN Grup, which includes El Mussol, Attic, QuQu and a total of 23 companies, remain optimistic after recording an increase in profits since the second half of the year and have a relatively solid outlook for Christmas sales.
Sources from the company stress that December 18 will also be a busy day, as there will be a pre-Christmas celebration among friends.
They added a Christmas menu to their six group menus, with a budget of €30 or more, as they noticed a trend of guests spending 10% more compared to last year in exchange for other items such as cava.
They also noted that companies are already appearing to recall their employees, and the size of the groups seems to be slightly larger.
Enric Goma, vice-president of Fecasarm (which includes institutions such as the Barcelona Bar, Restaurant and Leisure Centre Association), believes he is beginning to see the end of the tunnel and claims that the number of reservations has "revived", although clients are "dealing to the max".
This impression has not diminished during the Christmas season, whoever pays, he points out.
Pakistan 's nuclear program has caused great unrest in the United States .
Islamabad is producing nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country".
WikiLeaks documents confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the United States Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department published by Wikileaks confirms the extraordinary unrest that is being stirred up in Washington over Pakistan's nuclear program.
Besides providing clarifying and meaningful details about the content of the communications and the thoughts of the North American diplomats in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two states on nuclear security is "on the decline" rather than increasing, and that this unstable Asian country is producing "more nuclear weapons than any other state".
The peculiarity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that its weapons are not assembled but are stored in pieces to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack - is one of the main reasons for Washington's vigilance.
This is what Ambassador Anne W. Patterson to Pakistan calculated in a report prior to a visit by then-National Security Adviser James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to Taliban-controlled territory, the alleged dispersal of nuclear materials, and the vulnerability of nuclear materials transport".
The increased number of individuals associated with nuclear arsenals and missile programs is now being observed not only by the US but also by Russia as a widespread cause for caution.
"Pakistan has had to hire people of strict religious faith to protect nuclear facilities; with the decline in education and culture, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people to work in nuclear or missile programs", said Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev in a meeting with his US counterparts.
The biggest news in the documentation released by Julian Assange's server is the increasingly decreasing cooperation between the US and Pakistan on nuclear proliferation issues and the increased pace of Pakistani nuclear weapons production.
A May embassy dispatch that described communications with Pakistan as "frustrating" said: "Transparency often lacks; offers of help go unanswered or are rejected".
In another report, Peter Lavoy, a South Asia national intelligence officer, states that "despite economic disaster, Pakistan is developing nuclear weapons at the rate of no other country in the world".
Ambassador Petterson also asks Washington to make "very clear" during the visit of Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani that "the Pakistani military must stop its tacit support for terrorist groups".
The hunt for the Wikileaks boss
Obama is appointing a high-ranking official in charge of counterterrorism to prevent further leaks.
Interpol is issuing a "red alert" to track down and determine where Assange might be.
Everything about WikiLeaks and its founder Julian Assange is a complicated maze where it's hard to be certain of the facts.
Interpol yesterday issued an "emergency call", a so-called red notice, to "locate and track the movement" of Assange.
But this is not a standard arrest warrant.
Moreover, this call is not new, but dates back to November 20.
And it's not about the latest leak of more than a quarter million diplomatic documents, but about the sexual abuse charges an Australian is facing in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer for the creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, assures that "police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange".
It was on November 20th that the International Police Corps, based in Lyon, France, issued this order at the request of Sweden, but it was not made public until yesterday, when it received permission from the Swedish authorities.
In this situation, 188 countries have instructions for Interpol to identify or locate Assange "with a view to imposing temporary detention and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of a person who is subject to a red alert, many member states, the organisation explained, consider the so-called red notice to be an arrest - this must be ensured by the national police - especially if countries have a bilateral extradition agreement, as in the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is likely to be located.
This move was angered by Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a statement claiming that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder had expressed a willingness to answer questions from the Swedish authorities via videoconference.
They also recall that Assange requested and subsequently received permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, who they compare to the legendary Lavrenti Pavlovich Beria, head of Stalin's security.
"This is a hunt, not a legal pursuit", the letter states.
While the world is searching for him - and his mother is defending his innocence from Australia - Assange is still in the dark, but he is not silent.
On Monday, he gave an interview via Skype from an unknown location to the editor-in-chief of Time magazine, in which he demanded the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If she is found to be responsible for ordering U.S. diplomats to conduct espionage at the United Nations, in violation of international conventions to which the United States is a signatory, she should resign", he said.
His comments were rejected yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation request "ridiculous and absurd".
"I'm not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of the individual who runs the website", he told CNN.
Obama himself has assigned a senior counterterrorism official, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks.
President Barack Obama's intention to stop adding importance to Assange contrasts with the views being proclaimed by conservative politicians and commentators these days.
Peter King, a member of Congress who will chair the House National Security Committee from January, has asked the State Department to consider listing WikiLeaks as a terrorist organization "so that anyone who financially supports or otherwise assists them can be targeted and prosecuted".
Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian Prime Minister Stephen Harper, went further, saying that Assange should be "killed", which he subsequently recanted.
"Obama should put a reward on him or use a drone or something".
The one who didn't apologise was Mike Huckabee, a Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and potential presidential candidate.
"Whoever is in government, whoever is responsible for the leak, has committed treason, and any punishment other than execution would be too lenient", he told Fox News.
