The Republican leader will allow the party to vote in secret on its continuation.
Huguet proposes more plural executive and an end to the meeting system.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe for dealing with the internal revolt in the ERC, which has already been unsuccessful, losing 11 MPs and half the votes.
The President of the Party is aware that his gesture of resignation seems insufficient to the supporters of the former leader, José Luis Carrado-Rovira, and he also knows that the influence of this sector is now as weak as its leader himself, and that he absolutely cannot be concerned with the same as he was with other vanished currents.
So the leader of the Left will try to win new critics by winking, which will help him to turn in the municipal elections.
Puigcercós first announced yesterday that more than 200 members of the national committee will be able to vote in secret for him to remain in office.
With ballots, not by raising a hand.
If Carr's supporters want to pass a criminal vote to the president, they can do so without fear of retaliation.
The boss really wants to avoid the division and subjugation of his person.
In several interviews he stated that he would not consider himself confirmed with half the votes and one more, but added, without specifying the percentage, that it would not be a good result "after Bulgaria" either.
Carod's supporters are demanding more from the president than to make his office available - a gesture they consider of no weight, since Puigcercós controls the largest body at conventions.
But since they don't have enough votes to force the resignation, they're going to try to get the executive to recall the plan between now and May.
They therefore expect to participate in the preparation of a strategic reorientation document to be put to the vote by the management at the National Council on the 18th of the month.
Their goal is to support Puigcercós in exchange for promising to move the congress as early as the fall of 2011.
The ERC leader stated that "multilingualism" is detrimental to stability and that his goal is to ensure that the organization is able to wash its laundry behind closed doors once and for all.
In this context, an article written by current adviser Josep Huguet on his blog seems to be characteristic.
After considering Puigcercós' ideology, this innovation adviser took it for granted that the leader would be confirmed "in exchange for several goals".
And he named five, two of them excellent.
The first is to "recompile" the executive so that it represents at least 90% of the members, which means including new faces who are from the Carod-favorite sector.
The second target could be big news.
Huguet proposes that the ERC should completely abandon the meeting as a functioning mechanism.
So he's fighting for a constitutional reform to allow congresses to be held through elected delegates.
The end of the model of the meeting system, an exception in the Spanish system of political parties, is the intended goal of Puigcercós' team, which has already fought in this direction at the last two congresses.
However, the 2008 conciliation assembly decided that the meeting must be assessed at a special congress on constitutional reform.
This matter is still unresolved as the situation within the Party has deterred the resolution of this matter.
Now, with no critical sectors lurking, it might be a good time to re-engage with this matter and try to close it once and for all.
