China sticks to its greenhouse gas reduction target
The country's representative at the UN climate change conference COP16 assured that his country had made extraordinary efforts to reduce its carbon footprint, and made clear that it was insisting on its pledge to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% by 2020.
China will keep its pledge to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country's representative at the UN climate change conference.
In his first public speech at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the UNFCCC, Su Wei assured that his country had made an enormous effort to reduce its carbon footprint and transform its industry.
He said that his country had already invested $245 million in the past four years in an effort to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives and will continue to work with the international community on this issue.
He referred to the four pillars of the Chinese strategy on climate change: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
He said progress had already been made on all these points, including the adoption last year of a new energy law, which includes proposed targets for reducing greenhouse gas emissions.
It further underlined that in China, the federal authorities have worked in coordination with provincial and local authorities to achieve their energy saving, energy efficiency and emission reduction targets.
Furthermore, various multi-year plans are underway or have already been completed, which are financed by both the Chinese government and the governments of other states.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficiency Programme, which has been implemented over the past five years and has received investment from the UN, governments and private initiatives.
The provincial climate change project, the project to replace incandescent lamps with energy-efficient ones and the mitigation and adaptation project are also underway, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country's expert adviser on climate change, assured that China's efforts were greater than generally thought.
For example, he pointed out, China's per capita greenhouse gas emissions are 6 tons, while in the United States it's 100 tons; China is responsible for 9% of the historical share of emissions.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use - for example, it has increased energy efficiency by 20% over the last five years and expects to make further progress by 2020, he added.
