The United States changes the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centre before the interview at the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time shorter.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa processing process at the United States Embassies and Consulates will change.
The new procedure will require most applicants to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centre (ASC) before the interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information and it will be evaluated by the Consular Department prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including:
The total cost of the visa will be lower, with no more fees for arranging an appointment, processing the application and delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only a single fee covering all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for an applicant visa (including a temporary worker visa) and $390 for a business and investor visa.
People who want to renew their visas will not have to go through a consular interview, but will simply go to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
As the biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who require a second interview at the Consular Section will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for visas at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26 USD.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA announces the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The U.S. Space Agency has called a press conference tomorrow to present a discovery that could spell a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) of the United States will announce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that may confirm the theory of the existence of extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. by experts in astrobiology, the science that studies the origin, evolution, spread and future of life in space, at a press conference at NASA headquarters in Washington.
When inviting reporters, NASA assured them that it would present "a discovery that would cause a breakthrough in the search for extraterrestrial life", which aroused speculation from experts in other countries.
This discovery could confirm the theory that there are other creatures besides us, living in inhospitable conditions that were once considered uninhabitable, and that they might one day become intelligent creatures like humans if the conditions in which they live improve.
It appears to be a microbe that was found at the bottom of Lake Mono in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that has been considered too toxic for any form of life, since the lake is rich in arsenic.
The creature somehow uses arsenic for its life, and it's this ability that increases the likelihood that similar life could exist on other planets that don't have atmospheres like Earth's.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will prove that "there is another, another form of life, different from the one we know".
The Space Agency will announce the true impact of the findings at a press conference tomorrow.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who is studying the possibility of life on Mars; biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who are studying Titan (Saturn's largest moon) with the perspective that its chemical composition is similar to that on Earth.
