450 million without public tenders
Hydro-Québec has agreed, by mutual agreement, to award 450 million in contracts to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of over 100 contracts is a consortium of BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor,which has won the most significant contract, a contract to manage the entire project for a total of 295 million dollars without a public tender.
This consortium, Énergie gérance, was authorised in 2004, in parallel with the selection of Hydro-Québec, to entrust the private sector with the management of this major hydroelectric project worth USD 5 billion.
At the beginning of 2005, the Energy Management consortium won a lucrative contract without any call for competition.
For the Quebec side, the complaint against a consortium of undertakings poses a serious ethical problem which risks excluding competition and causing prices to rise.
"It's a new way to realize the collision and eliminate the competition".
"It means that people are no longer making side deals in secret, they are now making them openly", PQ MP Sylvain Simard told a press conference yesterday.
Earlier this morning, Mr. Simard asked the National Assembly this question because he says he is very concerned about how the public interest can be sold like this.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, objected this afternoon, strongly denying that this contract was a collusion.
"I have my own way", she said, claiming that PQ was "dishonest" and "lacking in accuracy".
She said it would be the least of her apologies to PQ.
The recipe for creating a consortium is common practice around the world.
This is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their mutual expertise in order to respond to a call for tenders for a complex project.
The Eastmain project is very complex, given the scale of the work.
Construction is already underway and must be completed by 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition being negotiated; it was a trade.
It must also be admitted that the consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the formula of the engineering consultancy consortium is the subject of a government investigation.
If we swiftly fly through the business register of Quebec companies, we can discover over 200 consortia, some of which seem to have been established.
This is how Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, namely CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to one and the same legal entity, and that is Dessau.
As regards the Énergie gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed in particular that 'the Bay James region is characterised by a special labour force dynamic and that Hydro-Québec has been responding to it since the 1970s'.
The main sponsor of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Baie James Energy Company (SEBJ), has given an explanation which forces us to face the fact that the contract for the management of the project was concluded by mutual agreement.
"If you go to a public tender and there are few tenderers bidding, your bids may be higher".
"You have two choices: you take the people who are in the contract as contestants, and you say, 'Let's make a deal that's satisfactory and good value.'
"But the main idea is that it is not the price that matters, but the competence of the people", Mr Laporte confirmed.
This contract awarded to the Énergie gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts worth more than $50,000 that the Parti Québécois has received.
The contracts were awarded to Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following the verification, Le Devoir counted 109 engineering consultancy contracts concluded between 2002 and March 2010 with companies or their branches, in particular with laboratories carrying out soil sample analysis.
SNC-Lavalin won 22 contracts, of which Génivar won 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10 without holding a stake in 'Energie gérance'.
