Worldwide plan for the restoration of lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to restore lighting in homes, shops and industrial spaces in 100 countries, with the goal of achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions that is nearly one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the planet's climate between now and 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of hard-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of the industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market, were replaced by fluorescent light bulbs or, better still, LEDs, a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet from lighting would be reversed.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from the entire fleet of cars on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, major countries with significant emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GHG emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we're going to have to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance sheet to stabilize global warming at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to avoid it getting out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated as heat and the remaining 5% is the product of light.
With fluorescent light bulbs, we reduce energy consumption by 75%, and with new LED bulbs, we reduce that consumption by a factor of two.
Fluorocompact bulbs have an average lifespan of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as the one Philips introduced this week - the company reportedly participated in a UN study - have a projected lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a burnt bulb, giving us a sense of the potential savings with a replacement plan that would apply in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent light bulbs, because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection centres.
However, the report states that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluorescent light bulb, but rather the thermal coal plants, which emit a lot of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in the light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation each year.
The report also details the benefits that each country would derive from this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants costing 2.5 billion to build.
