Vengeful Hackers and Avid Intelligence
The WikiLeaks case has a twofold significance.
On the one hand, there is a blatant scandal, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and it foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's move on.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks, is the confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service (of any nation) consists entirely of press cuts.
The "extraordinary revelations" of Americans about Berlusconi's sex life are what everyone has been reading in any newspaper for months (all but these two Berlusconi owned), and the unfortunate caricatured profile of Gaddafi has long been the subject of sketches for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret documents should only consist of reports that are already known is fundamental to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore that specializes in esoteric literature, you will find that each work repeats (the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Masons) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
Not only is the author of occult texts reluctant to seek out new information (or to find out where to look for information that does not exist), but those who practice it believe only what they already know and that confirms what they have learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same goes for classified documents.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited spirit) the head of the secret service (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, the editor of the newspaper Libération), who only believes what he admits to be true.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to a government agency was the same as that published by Newsweek a week earlier.
Why, then, was there so much hype about the disclosure of these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, that embassies, at least since the end of World War II and since heads of state can make phone calls or fly out for dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have been transformed into spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows very well that it is only out of hypocrisy that it seems to be ignored.
However, the fact that it is repeated in public disgraces the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker could get the most top-secret information in the most powerful country in the world is a severe blow, not insignificant, to the prestige of this government agency.
Scandal affects both victims and perpetrators.
But let's move on from there to the deep truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, it was possible to hold all power, like some Big Brother, controlling the every move of his people.
Orwell's prophecy has been proven since the ability to control every move by telephone, every transaction made, every hotel visited, the highway used, and so on, has made the citizen a complete victim of the crown of power.
But when we demonstrate, as we do now, that even the tombs of the most secret information of the powerful cannot withstand the intervention of some hacker, the control message ceases to be one-way and becomes a circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker - elected as a citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can power be maintained if it can no longer keep its own secrets?
It's true that Georg Simmel said that a true secret is a bottomless secret (and a bottomless secret can never be revealed); it's also true that any information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is a topless secret because it's pulled out of public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secret was a bottomless secret is to take away all of her power.
WikiLeaks didn't do anything wrong with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound to the endowed power?
Clearly, in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - that would be like posting it on a street corner poster.
But it's also quite obvious that with today's technology, it's pointless to hope that you can keep a message on the phone classified.
There's nothing easier than finding out if and when the head of state traveled by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future ?
I know that my prediction for now is science fiction, and therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials discreetly carrying out formalities on uncontrollable routes, carrying only the messages they know by heart or, rather, hiding precious information in the heel of their shoes.
The information will be kept in unique copies in key-locked drawers: overall, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology now moves sideways forward, which means backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutioned communications, the Internet rehabilitated the wire-based telegraph.
Video tapes (analog) allowed cinema lovers to record a film step by step, sliding it back and forth and revealing all the secrets of editing, whereas now CDs (digital) only allow you to jump through chapters, i.e. macroregions.
By express train, we can reach Milan from Rome in three hours, while the journey by airplane and the transportation it involves takes three and a half hours.
It is not surprising, then, that politics and communication technology are returning to horse-drawn carriages.
One last note.
Other times the press tried to understand what was being concealed in the embassy.
Now it's the embassies that are requesting confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France hacked its funding pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the progress made by developed countries in delivering on their promises of rapid unblocking (also called fast start) financing.
And the great French hacks were exposed
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the start of COP16, the EU pulled out the big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to funding fast start: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations, invaluable and valued for their true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it has made €2.2 billion available in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its pledge of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on the details, we find that things are much more complicated.
The financing is 'new and additional' under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is realised without detriment to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
The European Commission, for example, has taken 2009 as a reference year: international funding has been maintained and it is adding 150 million to the three-year Fast Start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with ODA deadlines.
In contrast, France considers that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the overall level of public development aid d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of aid granted by France to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even decrease) in order to comply with its commitment to finance 'new and additional' ...
Another crucial element is the distribution of gifts and loans.
There's no rule yet, and everyone chooses their own way of calculating.
Some, like France, think that 1 euro lent is equal to 1 euro given.
Obviously, it's hard to prove: the effort is incomparable.
If the use of loans can be demonstrated for certain investments which are profitable (often these are emission reduction projects involving more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro we receive as equivalent to one euro we give... , we should not understand it as the title of our commitments but as the price of the loan to the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only justify itself by saying that it 'meets' its commitment of €420 million, of which 91.5% is a loan (€389.8 million) and 8.5% is a donation (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan on such a scale.
Germany has claimed 46% of the funds, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) are fulfilling their commitments with 100% of the donations.
In other words, if the absolute majority of the European Union gives 1 euro to fulfill its promise, France gives only 10 cents and considers this effort to be comparable.
A beautiful piece of cake!
In summary, France's 'fast start' financing is based on a double-entry approach: on the one hand, the stock's evolution over time and, on the other, the real financial burden.
Although it spends only €36.1 million, it can convince that it spends €420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why should member states continue to donate when all they need is to lend?) and in negotiations because developing countries are not completely naive...
The early funding chapter is just a small issue, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not our case.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its accounting practices for 2011 and 2012, in line with its commitments and in a spirit of decency and fairness towards other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussions on long-term financing contributions (another key chapter currently under discussion): we will not avoid the question of 'sufficiency' or the way in which loans are accounted for.
France should change its attitude to become as progressive in these deposits as it is in others.
So everyone's hopes are in the new environment minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizeta, who is coming to Cancun next week.
The surprise announcement of a fast start by France and its vision of 'additionality' and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international trust necessary to move forward in the discussions.
Alert about pesticides that children will ingest.
A 10-year-old child will ingest 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study released Wednesday by the Future Generations Association.
The association, which points out that its results "are not of significant statistical value given the low number of samples analysed but are characteristic of the problem being addressed", bought between July and September four meals of food normally consumed and one light meal as a light snack per child for about a decade in supermarkets in L'Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, which include the official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day - as well as sweets, have been analysed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other polluting agents.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are classified as clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptors to the PE glands, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we can clearly see in our research that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking", the association states.
Breakfast butter and milk tea alone contain about ten residues with potential carcinogenic effects and three that have been shown to be certain carcinogens, as well as about 20 residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apples imported from Brazil, which the study described as a snack, contained traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans included in the lunch, which the study found to contain strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, ground beef, canned tuna, and even caterpillars and chewing gum were sprayed with pesticides and other chemicals.
The tap water was tested for nitrate and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not escape analysis.
The final risk to consumers of this 'cocktail of contaminants' is probably underestimated,' the study concludes.
The Green Europe Group (EE-LV) has proposed a moratorium on pesticides to stop the "growth of civilization diseases" in the "face of an emergency".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of which were in cereals.
